les":"Wales","Anglesley, Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales":"Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales"},"da":{"1455–1538":"1455–1538","1444–1486":"1444–1486","1463–1485":"1463–1485","1483–1515":"1483–1515","1430–1454":"1430–1454","1430–1467":"1430–1467","1483":"1483","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","1454":"1454","1486":"1486","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1463":"1463","about 1443":"omkring 1443","about 1485":"omkring 1485","1538":"1538","1515":"1515","Abberffaw, Anglesley, Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom":"Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Anglesley, Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales":"Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales"},"nl":{"1455–1538":"1455–1538","1444–1486":"1444–1486","1463–1485":"1463–1485","1483–1515":"1483–1515","1430–1454":"1430–1454","1430–1467":"1430–1467","1483":"1483","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","1454":"1454","1486":"1486","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1463":"1463","about 1443":"circa 1443","about 1485":"circa 1485","1538":"1538","1515":"1515","Abberffaw, Anglesley, Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom":"Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wales":"Wales","Anglesley, Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales":"Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales"},"en":{"1455–1538":"1455–1538","1444–1486":"1444–1486","1463–1485":"1463–1485","1483–1515":"1483–1515","1430–1454":"1430–1454","1430–1467":"1430–1467","1483":"1483","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","1454":"1454","1486":"1486","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1463":"1463","about 1443":"about 1443","about 1485":"about 1485","1538":"1538","1515":"1515","Abberffaw, Anglesley, Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom":"Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Anglesley, Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales":"Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Howell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh and English: in the Welsh border counties, from the Welsh male personal name <i>Hywel</i> ‘eminent’, popular since the Middle Ages particularly in honor of the great 10th-century law-giving Welsh king. The name may also arise from the Breton personal name <i>Houuel</i>, <i>Huwel</i>, <i>Huwal</i>, <i>Howael</i>, cognate with the Welsh name. Bretons were especially numerous in the eastern counties of England. See   Powell  .","English: perhaps from a Middle English personal name <i>Huwel</i> (spelled <i>Howel</i>), a shortening of <i>Huwelot</i> or <i>Huelin</i> (see   Hewlett   and   Huling  ), both pet forms of Middle English <i>Huw</i> (see   Hugh  ).","English: habitational name from Howell (Lincolnshire), from an uncertain initial element + Old English <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’."],"variants":[{"name":"Howle","meanings":["English and Welsh:","variant of   Howell  .","variant of   Hole  ."]},{"name":"Howells","meanings":["English and Welsh (Glamorgan): variant of   Howell  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent English <i>-s</i>.","English: perhaps occasionally a nickname for someone who was fearless, from Middle English <i>houe</i>, <i>houwe</i> ‘anxiety, fear’ (Old English <i>hogu</i> or <i>hoga</i>) + <i>les</i> ‘less’. If this has survived as a modern surname, its pronunciation has been influenced by that of the name in 1 above.","English: variant of   Holes  ."]},{"name":"Powell","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Hywel</i> ‘son of <i>Hywel</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘eminent’ (see   Howell  ).","Irish: mainly of Welsh origin as in 1 above, but sometimes a surname adopted as equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Phóil</b> ‘son of the servant of Saint Paul’ (see   Guilfoyle  ).","English: variant of   Paul   or   Poole  ."]}]},{"name":"Rowland","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roland  , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that given name in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Roland","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. In Old French literature it is borne by a legendary Frankish hero, a vassal of Charlemagne, whose exploits are told in the <i>Chanson de Roland</i>. The subject of the poem is Roland's death at the Battle of Roncesvalles in the Pyrenees in  778 , while protecting the rearguard of the Frankish army on its retreat from Spain. Roland is depicted in literature and legend as headstrong and impulsive. His devoted friendship with the prudent  Oliver  is also legendary."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Rowland ap Howell was born in 1455, in Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Hywel ap Gruffydd, was 25 and his mother, Margred ferch Gruffydd, was 25. He had at least 1 daughter with Annes ferch Dafydd. He died in 1538, in his hometown, at the age of 83."},"et":{"1455–1538":"1455–1538","1444–1486":"1444–1486","1463–1485":"1463–1485","1483–1515":"1483–1515","1430–1454":"1430–1454","1430–1467":"1430–1467","1483":"1483","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","1454":"1454","1486":"1486","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1463":"1463","about 1443":"umbes 1443","about 1485":"umbes 1485","1538":"1538","1515":"1515","Abberffaw, Anglesley, Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom":"Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Anglesley, Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales":"Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales"},"fi":{"1455–1538":"1455–1538","14